# Items Module Rules

## Purpose
Manages the game's item system including equipment, consumables, crafting materials, and quest items. Inspired by classic RPG inventory systems.

## Item Categories

### Equipment
Equipment modifies derived stats when worn. Uses the `statModifiers: Partial<DerivedStats>` field.
Gear that can be equipped to slots:
- **Weapon**: Equipped in hand slot, modifies attack
- **Armor**: Body protection, reduces damage taken
- **Head/Body/Hands/Feet**: Armor piece slots
- **Accessory**: Rings, amulets, belts - passive bonuses

### Consumables
Single-use items with immediate effects via `ConsumableEffect` discriminator:
- **Healing Potions**: Restore HP (heal, heal-large, heal-full)
- **Mana Potions**: Restore MP (restore-mana, restore-mana-large, restore-mana-full)
- **Buff Potions**: Temporary stat boosts (buff-body, buff-mind, buff-heart, buff-all-stats, buff-defense, buff-attack)
- **Throwing Items**: Combat consumables (damage-bomb, damage-poison, damage-fire)
- **Utility**: cure-debuff, revive, restore-all

Track quantity - consuming items decrement count.

### Materials
Crafting components (future system):
- Gathered from world or enemy drops
- Stack by quantity
- Used in crafting recipes

### Quest Items
Story-critical items:
- Cannot be sold or discarded
- Associated with specific quests
- Often unique/key items

## Type Guards
Use discriminated unions and type guards:
```typescript
if (isEquipment(item)) {
    equip(item.slot, item);
}
if (isStackable(item)) {
    stack(item.id, item.quantity);
}
```

## Implementation Guidelines

### Item Definition (Library Files)
Item templates are stored in JSON files and loaded via `item.library.ts`:
- `consumable.library.json` — All consumable definitions
- `equipment.library.json` — All equipment definitions
- `item.library.ts` — Registry loader with O(1) lookups

### Inventory Operations (Reducers)
State-modifying operations in `item.reducer.ts`:
- `addItemToInventory(state, item)` → GameState (auto-stacks if stackable)
- `removeItemFromInventory(state, itemId)` → GameState (auto-unequips if equipped)
- `useConsumable(state, itemId)` → GameState (applies effect + decrements quantity)
- `stackItem(state, itemId, amount)` → GameState
- `equipItem(state, itemId)` → GameState (applies stat modifiers)
- `unequipItem(state, slot)` → GameState (removes stat modifiers)
- `mergeStackableItem(state, item)` → GameState

### Utility Functions (index.ts)
Non-state-modifying helpers:
- `getEquipmentStatBonuses(equippedItems)` → Partial<DerivedStats>
- `findInventoryItem(state, itemId)` → Item | undefined
- `getInventoryByCategory(state, category)` → Item[]

## File Organization
- `index.ts` — Public exports (types, type guards, library lookups, reducer functions)
- `types.ts` — Item type hierarchy (BaseItem, Equipment, Consumable, Material, QuestItem, EquippedItems)
- `item.reducer.ts` — Inventory state operations (pure functions returning GameState)
- `item.library.ts` — Registry loader and lookup functions
- `consumable.library.json` — Consumable definitions
- `equipment.library.json` — Equipment definitions
- `.cursorrules` — This file

## Loot Tables
A simple system to determine enemy drops:
- Enemies have a stat called `loot`
- When an enemy is defined, list all possible drops in `loot`
- When enemy dies in combat, provide player with n-rolls on the `loot` list
- Player will roll after combat to get drops
